 for stub methods could work, but I’m unsure about potential dynamic-access coverage.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Investigating Gradle build process**\\n\\nI’m considering how the Gradle Native Build Tools agent collects configuration during tests and supplies it to nativeTestCompile. It seems that javaTest might run to generate config for stubs. In this repository, nativeTestCompile may depend on the test agent. The existing build generates resources in build/native/generated. However, the dynamic-access runner likely doesn't. The user has specified not to compile or run, and the workflow handles tasks in order, so I’ll inspect the generated native config for test inclusions.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_mr8135qTR0zxVB0hFi2naird|fc_0a6d7ded2727a5060169f261f57e0c8194bb840c797581822f", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "find tests/src/org.jgroups/jgroups/5.2.0.Final/src/test/resources -type f -maxdepth 10 -print 2>/dev/null || true && find tests/src/org.jgroups/jgroups/5.2.0.Final -path '*reflect-config.json' -type f | head -20"}, "partialJson": "{\"command\":\"find tests/src/org.jgroups/jgroups/5.2.0.Final/src/test/resources -type f -maxdepth 10 -print 2>/dev/null || true && find tests/src/org.jgroups/jgroups/5.2.0.Final -path '*reflect-config.json' -type f | head -20\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 17113, "output": 916, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 18029, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777492452965, "responseId": "resp_0a6d7ded2727a5060169f261e5adc88194848b9807fa145392"}}
